<div id="review_23251914" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/23251914" />
    <a title="Erick" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/184356-erick"><img alt="Erick" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1443213693p2/184356.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/23251914?book_show_action=true">May 29, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Erick" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Erick" href="/user/show/184356-erick">Erick</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/4659.A_Widow_for_One_Year">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer23251914" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14443575341474448617">The first couple hundred pages of the book, before it jumps forward several decades, are the most even, and it is this part of the story that is most endearing. This first part introduces us to the story&apos;s three or four main characters and chronicles their shared summer of 1958--a summer which, you guessed it, has profound effects on the rest of all their lives.<br/><br/>And it is much of the rest of these lives that Irving takes us through in the remaining four hundred pages, and due to the front-heavy n</span>
  <span id="freeText14443575341474448617" style="display:none">The first couple hundred pages of the book, before it jumps forward several decades, are the most even, and it is this part of the story that is most endearing. This first part introduces us to the story's three or four main characters and chronicles their shared summer of 1958--a summer which, you guessed it, has profound effects on the rest of all their lives.<br /><br />And it is much of the rest of these lives that Irving takes us through in the remaining four hundred pages, and due to the front-heavy nature of the book's dramatic set-up it's probably unavoidable that the follow-through seems noticeably lacking in some intensity.<br /><br />But I was still happy to follow the characters along, and for the most part they all seem to end up in their correct places. I didn't buy every plot turn/twist (and the shaky pages set in Amsterdam make it clear that Irving is far more at home in his native New England), but Irving is a great storyteller and easily convinces the reader to weather the impressive storm of plot mechanics he (again) rouses to move things along. All in all: An enjoyable read, but pick up the more-satisfying <i>Prayer for Owen Meany</i> first.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14443575341474448617" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


