<span id="freeTextContainer7131392696534692970">In my late teens and early twenties I used to read Irving&apos;s books all the time, I think I must&apos;ve read &quot;a widow for one year&quot; at least 4 or 5 times - it was one of my favourite books of his. I&apos;d recently decided to read it again (it&apos;s been years...), this time in English. It&apos;s not the book I used to love. Or maybe I&apos;m not the person I used to be. It&apos;s been a surreal experience. The story, the characters, the language, nothing was like it used to be. It was like reading two different books on the</span>
  <span id="freeText7131392696534692970" style="display:none">In my late teens and early twenties I used to read Irving's books all the time, I think I must've read "a widow for one year" at least 4 or 5 times - it was one of my favourite books of his. I'd recently decided to read it again (it's been years...), this time in English. It's not the book I used to love. Or maybe I'm not the person I used to be. It's been a surreal experience. The story, the characters, the language, nothing was like it used to be. It was like reading two different books on the same subjects... My younger me used to give ***** to this book without hesitation. Now I would've given it ***. So 4 stars it is. (Part of me wonders if I used to love this book BECAUSE of its Polish translation, hence my disappointment with the original, or whether I've outgrown his writing in general 🤔)</span>
  <a data-text-id="7131392696534692970" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
